</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usharlis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sharlis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#333333>(2/8/01 10:36:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=148.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Questions on Mage strategy for Vox</span><hr size=1> Okie, finally I've got the time to sit down and respond to this post again.<br>
<br>
First off, I have only been on three Vox raids. Two were TPW's and the third was a success. That said, I really don't think I'm an expert on the subject but I can at least try to answer your questions based on my experience.<br>
<br>
Before I go into your questions take a moment to look at this map:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://mail.futurelnk.net/~kolabair/graphics/voxmap.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
NOTE: The red stars mark where there are PITS where you will most certainly fall to your death if you fall in them. You'll fall to the area below Vox which is filled with all kinds of mobs like spiders and tentacle terrors and such. CR from this area is very difficult so stay away from these pits!<br>
<br>
Now, on to your questions:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1) Where should I bind? I've read that casters will bind in the prep area, so if they die they can mem a couple spells grab a malachite or two and run back into the battle to summon another pet or nuke. Sounds strange but is this an appropriate tactic?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The area you bind is marked &quot;Staging Spot&quot; in blue on the above map. From the &quot;Monk FD spot&quot; there is a path that goes up, like a ramp. This is the spot where you bind in. The pathway leading east from that spot is also a ramp up.<br>
<br>
Should you die during the raid (and you most likely will <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) summon yourself some food or something, and head right back into the lair and continue on with the fight.<br>
<br>
NOTE: Should you for some reason aggro Vox, DO NOT GO NEAR THIS SPOT! You probably know better than to do this but I feel the need to say it because on the second raid I went on, someone stupidly trained Vox to the bind point where all the casters and clerics were bound. This resulted in a horrible cycle of death! I myself died seven times that night. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2) I am currently lvl 48 ... should I even bother using a pet? I understand that pets below the lvl 49 summonings will constantly fall victim to the Dragon's fear. If not I guess I should get lvl 49 before Sunday.  If the pet does get feared should I click my Earthen Boots to kill it off or is there no real threat of it training something back to the group?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
On every Vox raid I've been on, pets have not been allowed. The reason? Because some people just don't know how to control their pets. While fighting the giants up to Vox's lair, if a pet wanders away, there is a potential to aggro Vox. If this happens, you're in for a bad time so most raid leaders just eliminate the risk. If you do summon a pet and it does get feared, you probably won't be able to do anything about it because you'll be feared too.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 3) Which pet is good to use for Vox? Earth for the HPs? Water for the possible CR and average stats? And when should the pet be summoned? Before the fight so it can get some MR and CR buffs or after Vox has been engaged? Also, is it normal to send the pet in right away or wait for the raid leader to call for the casters to start nuking?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, if the raid leader does let you use a pet, I would recommend fire first, then air. I recommend fire because of the unresistable damage shield. Your pet's spells won't be able to damage her anyway but in case you want to try it, the air pet will give an opportunity to stun her. Vox is a caster, so take any opportunity to interrupt her. <br>
<br>
I can only answer the other questions with assumptions - but I would think that the pets are summoned around the &quot;Monk FD Spot&quot;. Then, a few seconds after the tanks are sent in, the pets would be sent in, followed by the casters when Vox is at 60% or below health.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 4) Is there some kind of a step up for the Malise line and do the Shaman's usually have a hand in it? By step up I mean Malise first, then Malisement, then Malosi. Does this matter or should I just cast Malisement until (or never I guess) it sticks?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Generally the Shaman will be casting the Malise spell. If there is no shaman present, then they will call on the mage that has the highest malise spell (in this case, Malosi which is level 51).  The malise spell is really only for the Ice Giants though. Vox has an unbelievably high MR and it's doubtful that you'll be able to get any spell to stick at all.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 5) What nuke should I use? Blaze? Lava Bolt (assuming I get lvl 49 prior to Sunday)? SoS?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, like I said in the previous answer - Vox has an unbelievably high MR and it's doubtful that you'll be able to get any spell to stick at all. So you shouldn't have to worry about what nuke to use on her. On Ice Giants, however , you should be able to affect them just fine. I do *not* recommend lava bolt, since you need a clear line of sight, and you won't get it with a billion tanks surrounding it. You'll probably end up casting Shock of Swords.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If there is anything I should be aware of and have left out please feel free to insert your comments and experience. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, I will - and these aren't set in stone rules, they are just my friendly advice <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> :<br>
<br>
1. Do not go on the raid expecting experience or loot. If you do, you will probably be disappointed, unless you happen to get very lucky and outroll the other 20 casters who want the same item you do. Go for the experience of attending a large raid and taking down a difficult mob <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
2. Get your resist gear beforehand. They say you should have at LEAST an 80 cold resist BEFORE buffs. Invest in some jewelry that gives sv cold. Replace intelligence items if you have to. Vox has a nasty cold area affect spell that will have your life down to a bubble before you know it. Cold resist gear helps some. Also, magic resist will help with the fears.<br>
<br>
Talk to a jeweler about what kind of cold and magic resist gear they can make for you. Also if you can, keep on the lookout for items in auctions. There are always resist items being sold, some more expensive than others.<br>
<br>
3. Listen to the raid leader. Groups should be designated at the beginning of the raid, and the raid leader should also appoint a leader of each group. If you have questions or concerns, try asking the leader of your group before you ask the leader of the raid. Also, try not to use /ooc or /shout unless absolutely necessary. This leaves these channels free for the pullers and such and also helps eliminate scroll.<br>
<br>
4. Do not loot anything unless you are the group leader. Don't even look at a corpse! Accidents happen, and it's just not worth the headache to satisfy curiosity.<br>
<br>
5. The mage is useful on a dragon raid because they can - a. summon mod rods, and b. fireshield. I'd keep them up at all times.<br>
<br>
I can't really think of anything else. I hope you have a good time <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Sharlis~<br>
